        <marginalia anchor_text="Archimedes" hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Archimedis ingens, et stupenda Polymechania. Opera egregij, et terribilis Artificis. 
                        Archimedis interempti honorificus respectus. i[nfr]a, 387.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Archimedes"/>
                    <internal_ref>
                        <target ref="PrincetonPA6452:00000409" text="387"/>
                    </internal_ref>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Archimedes’ great and astonishing engineering. Works of an excellent and formidable craftsman. 
                [For] the respectful regard for Archimedes after he was killed. [See] below, 387.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Fabrilium, aliarumq[ue] machinationum rarissima exempla: ex intimis geometrarum, et architectorum artificijs. 
                        Nec dubium est, mirabilia fuisse, qua[e] Romani milites, ducesq[ue] tantoperè stupebant, et pa[e]nè perhorrescebant. 
                        Da Marcellum, quem nihil humanarum artium, operumve perterrefecit.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Unique examples of engineering and other machines, from the most inner works of geometrians and architects. 
                And there is no doubt that those which so amazed and almost terrified the Roman soldiers and leaders were extraordinary ones. 
                Except Marcellus, who was not frightened of any human crafts or works.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
